	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Anti-competitive practices dominate agricultural trade in Central African Republic  </h1>

			
			<h4>
												16 September 2013
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>In its latest Trade Policy Review (TPR) of the Central African Republic (CAR), the WTO Secretariat finds that agriculture in the CAR is in a poor state, with only 5.3% of the potential arable area actually being cultivated, equivalent to less than 0.5 ha per agricultural worker. As a consequence, “more than 50% of the value of imports into the CAR comprises agricultural products and foodstuffs”. Farmers face “the constant risks of looting and destruction by armed gangs”: as a consequence, “farmers limit their wheat cultivation to what is needed for their own consumption,” for example. This comes on top of the common challenges faced across a number of CEMAC countries – poor roads, very low usage of agricultural inputs, lack of storage capacity, weak agricultural credit systems and an inadequate legal framework, with these challenges even more acute in CAR than elsewhere in CEMAC.</p><p>The WTO TPR observes that “anti-competitive practices are rampant” in CAR’s agricultural trade, reflecting “the small number of economic operators who are both importers and transporters”. This has a direct effect on the welfare of urban households, whose food needs “are primarily met through imports from neighbouring countries”. </p><p>Protection of local farmers from import competition appears at first sight to be high. In addition to the protection offered by the CEMAC common external tariff, derogations for some products allow higher import tariffs to be applied. On top of this the TPR finds several cases where CAR is “in breach of the principle of national treatment” by imposing higher domestic taxes on imports than local production. Locally produced meat, fruit and vegetables, for example, are exempt from VAT, while imports are not; and a 10% excise duty is applied in theory to all non-alcoholic beverages, but in practice not collected on domestic output. </p><p>Because of complex differences in treatment between items, this apparent local preference is not always the case: domestic meat processing, for example, appears to suffer from negative tariff escalation, with tariffs on the unprocessed products higher than on processed products. The TPR also calculates that the tariff applied to inputs for the edible fat sector are higher than those on imports of the finished product. It concludes that “the imposition of selective taxes on some agricultural products and not others creates distortions and inequalities between products”, and thus “detracts from the economic efficiency” of the sector.&nbsp;<i>&nbsp;</i></p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>WTO, ‘Trade Policy Review: Cameroon, Congo, Gabon, Central African Republic and Chad; Annex 4’, 29 and 31 July 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.wto.org/english/tratop_e/tpr_e/tp385_e.htm" target="_self">http://www.wto.org/english/tratop_e/tpr_e/tp385_e.htm</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The section of the WTO TPR dealing with the CAR highlights the situation in the sugar sector, which provides an extreme example of the difficult choices facing governments that want to increase output by giving one company a monopoly. Since 2003, a single, French-owned private sector company has benefited from a package of government assistance and a trade policy regime that grants it “a 90% monopoly on sugar imports”. This regime has seen an increase in production from 3,600 tonnes in 2004 to 11,154 tonnes in 2011.</p><p>However, the production figure reached falls short of the target established in the 2003 Memorandum of Understanding (15,000 tonnes by 2012–13) and falls far short of domestic consumption (estimated at 30,000 tonnes). This relative underperformance has been achieved at considerable financial cost, with the company enjoying “full exemption from corporate income tax”. As the TPR points out, the granting of monopoly rights for 90% of permitted sugar imports is “hardly compatible with the WTO Agreement” or with CEMAC rules.&nbsp;</p>
		</div>
		
